Workaround for when mezzanine is hosted under a different urlspace. (Only tested with Django admin, not grappelli)The keywords.js file needs to reference a mezzanine URL, from the admin site.nIt used to use a hard-coded string with a root-absolute path, but this failed when mezzanine was hosted elsewhere.nInstead, we now reference a global Mezzanine JS object, which is set by template, using URL reversal to find the correct url.nThis requires a reworking in how the PageAdmin object accesses its Media settings - previously the list of js files was calculated at module load time, but at this stage the url reversal mechanism won't work, because the urls.py aren't all loaded yet, Instead, we hide the list generation inside a lazy iterator object and create the list on demand.n

Fixed admin page tree on reload.The problem occured when reloading a page after setting an open child branch'snparent as closed. When you reloaded a page the routine that wouldnreopen previously opened child branches (that are currently hidden by a parent)nwas causing said child branch displaying both the show(+) and hide(-)nicons side by side which could be seen when reopening the parent.nIt would also cause this said hidden, opened child branchnto no longer be registered in the opened branch cookie. So if you were tonreload the page again, this branch wouldn't be opened at all.nnThe solution involves simply reopening all previously opened branches onnreload without worrying about adding their ID's again to the cookie. It alsonavoids using the Jquery toggle() function which seemed to be the problemnthat caused both the show(+) and hide(-) buttons to appear.n

Allow pages to be dragged out of a subtree to the root level in page admin.
Check that setting a new page parent won't cause a cycle in the parent-child graph. Such cycles lead to an infinite loop in ``Page.save`` (e.g. python process consuming all resources).

Protect sequences provided or generated for the default value of ``MenusField`` from being forced to unicode (as for example u'[1, 2, 3]'). Django forces fields defaults to unicode unless they're callable (see ``Field.get_default``). This is done to prevent problems that could arise from setting the same mutable object as a default for many fields (see Django ticket #18478).

Use CSS instead of JavaScript for the admin app dropdownsThere were some bugs with the dropdowns when they were in JavaScript:nn  1.  When you open a dropdown and then scroll, the dropdown would stayn  put, instead of following the scroll.nn  2.  The JavaScript used `.live('mouseover')` which binds to body andn  wastes memory because it's fired for mouseover on every single DOMn  element.nn  3.  Occasionally, the dropdowns never disappeared even after mouseout.nnThis commit fixes those bugs by using CSS and `:hover` instead ofnJavaScript.  Additionally, it simplifies the JavaScript related tonsetting the href of the primary menu item links to their first child.nnIt is a pixel for pixel match of the previous functionality andnappearance.n

Replaced the BLOG_URLS_USE_DATE setting with a new BLOG_URLS_DATE_FORMAT setting - it can contain the string year, month, or day, which controls the date granularity in blog post URLs.

Editable settings refactor - this change is to clear up confusion around editable settings being defined in a project's settings module. Previously when this happened, the settings.py module value would only serve as a default, which would be superceded by the db editable value as soon as the settings admin form is first saved. To address this, this change means that editable settings defined in the project's settings.py module now mark the setting as not editable, so it will always be the value used. We also include some handling for the migration case so that even with this change, editable settings already in the db that have a settings.py value defined will still use the db value and provide a warning.
Revert the handling for still using db values for editable settings with settings.py values defined, since it basically defeats the purpose if a settings.py value is added once a project is live.

Allow for there being no errors in the twitter api response.When a successful user query to the twitter api is completed the json that is returned is a list.nIn order to validate the response the code tests to see if it was a dictionary with an error key.nHowever passing a string as a index to a list will raise a TypeError, which was not being caught by the except clause.nnI have added TypeError to the list of items being caught. There are of course other ways of verifying the response but I think just adding the TypeError is in keeping with what you have already done.nnFor reference, here is what I was seeing:nn> python manage.py poll_twitter --traceback --forcenTraceback (most recent call last):n  ...n  File /.../lib/python2.7/site-packages/mezzanine/twitter/models.py, line 74, in runnraise TwitterQueryException(tweets[errors][0][message])nTypeError: list indices must be integers, not strn

Render form errors with a new {% errors_for %} template tag.This new template tag accomplishes three things:nn- Fixes the bug of multiple form error messages appearing when usingn{% fields_for %}. This bug was intruduced in [this commit](https://github.com/jerivas/mezzanine/commit/323660db5bee7e21358315c4e247eaa8ee77b034)nand was discovered when [migrating Cartridge to BS3](https://github.com/clemensbasti/cartridge/pull/1)n- Decouples error message rendering from form field rendering, withnthe added flexibility of placing the error messages wherever we want.n- Creates a new template (includes/form_errors.html) as the singlenlocation to control form error rendering through all Mezzanine andnCartridge.n
Admin href disqus recent comments to https or http via double slashChanged how the disqus widget in the admin panel loads its recentncomments. This will fix any errors for loading insecure content.n

settings.py: additional checks for ImportError when importing local_settingsIn its current state, settings.py catches and ignores all ImportErrors whennloading the local settings. While this behavior was intended to deal withna missing local_settings.py, it also hides ImportErrors caused by importnstatements *inside* local_settings.py, e.g.  for setting up deployment-specificnldap authentication.nnThis simple fix will rethrow any ImportErrors that don't have local_settingsnin their message.n

Renamed all ``get_query_set`` methods to ``get_queryset``.Django 1.6 normalized the naming, providing a metaclass that handlesnprevious naming schemes, while printing a warning. See:nhttps://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/15363nnThis is probably incompatible with 1.5, but limits the amount ofnDjango 1.8 deprecation warnings.n

Added a simple decorator defining ``get_query_set`` or ``get_queryset`` allowing to use the latter one while preserving compatibility with 1.5.Django (1.6+) uses a metaclass to allow usage of the former name afternrenaming a method (``django.utils.deprecation.RenameMethodsBase``), butnfor the 2 cases in Mezzanine a decorator seems sufficient and lessnintrusive.n

Replaced usage of Options.get_(add|change|delete)_permission with auth.get_permission_codename. Just a single case in utils/views.py.The former one is deprecated and will be removed in Django 1.8; seenhttps://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/20642.n
Added an 1.5-compatible implementation of get_permission_codename.
Made forms tests use Mezzanine's TestCase.Not currently necessary, but potentially surprising if you add somethingnto the TestCase.n
Made MenusField respect the current value of PAGE_MENU_TEMPLATES_DEFAULT.
Made MenusField also support dynamic changes to PAGE_MENU_TEMPLATES.This costs a call to a private Field._get_choices(), becausenField.choices is already a property.n
Small semantic change in MenusField behavior, now in_menus returns an empty tuple instead of None for a page not in any menu.This seems more consistent with PAGE_MENU_TEMPLATES_DEFAULT = tuple().n
Cleaned up in_menus defaults test.Making use of the runtime settings changes support.n
Replaced page.login_required handling by redirect_to_login shortcut from contrib.auth to support LOGIN_URL set to a view, view name or a translation proxy.

Extended the test_login_required to check if LOGIN_URL set to view or pattern name still allows the decorator to work as expected.The new cases are only checked if mezzanine.accounts is installed.nnThese additional LOGIN_URL possibilities were introduced in 1.5; viewnobjects should also work, but don't seem to be documented.n
Don't test the new options with 1.4, it's not supposed to support them.

In the admin dropdown menu, show add links to users without change permissionsThis is a patch to fix the following problem:nn1. Create a user with add permissions but not change permissions on a modeln   that is managed through the admin (e.g. blog posts).n2. Log in as that user in the admin site.n3. Click on the name of the model in the dropdown menu on the left.n4. Error.nnThe problem arises because the template uses the admin_url instead of thenadd_url for users without appropriate permissions to change instances of thenmodel. It then tries to remedy the situation by manually appending 'add/' tonthe url. However, the url it receives from the template tag admin_url is setnto 'None'.n

Fix: Add missing space

Fix file name decoding from zip files in python 3.In python3, non-ascii filenames in galleries are incorrectly decoded,ninterpreting utf8 code points as box-drawing characters. For example, innthe demo project Au00ccu0081vila Spain is incorrectly parsed as Au00e2u0095u00a0u00c3u00bcvila Spain.nnCP437 is a superset of ascii and the de facto standard for file names.nObviously not every valid utf-8 character is in this character set, butna lot of tooling does not support file names with characters outsidenthis set anyway. If we were to encode them in a broader character set Insuspect we would get into OS-interoperability issues, so better tonforego encoding them and coerce them into valid file names.nnNote that this changes the behavior such that in python3, file names arennow decoded with a chardet-detected encoding.nnIt's also notable that the latest release of chardet incorrectlynidentifies the encoding, so in the demo galleries, Au00ccu0081vila Spain isnincorrectly parsed as Au00c4u009avila Spain. This is fixed in chardet master.n

Correctly handle custom email fields in mezzanine.formsThe `is_a` method checks whether a field is one of Mezzanine's built-innform fields. As far as I can tell, every other usage is for the purposenof initializing the built-in fields and widgets, so it makes sense tonexclude user-defined fields.nnHowever in this instance, we only want to know whether the field is annEmailField, not that it is *the* built-in Mezzanine email field.nTherefore, check the class rather than identity.nnThe effective change here is that user-defined fields (innFORMS_EXTRA_FIELDS) which subclass django's EmailField will be able tonreceive confirmation emails.n

Richtext filters must return SafeString.For now, just raise a warning. In the way-off future I'd like to seenrichtext_filters raise an exception when a SafeString is not received.nnDjango makes a contract with users: Unless you explicitly marknuntrusted input as safe, we'll escape it and you don't need to worrynabout XSS vulnerabilities. My position is that reusable apps shouldnproxy this contract to users.nnIn doing so, this also moves the SafeString conversion out of templatesnand into the `escape` function in which bleach actually makes the htmlnsafe.  The closer these two components are to each other the less likelynwe are to make a mistake in between them.n
